ce:section.ce:para:
For copper printing, we found the composition table (Table 1
                     ) provided on the datasheet of the filament to be insufficient. Therefore, we applied non-destructive X-ray fluorescence (XRF) analysis to determine its composition. During the examination, we used a cylindrical test piece printed for leak testing, analyzing a 1 mm2 area on its surface. The X-ray tube and detector operated for 2000 seconds during the measurement. The spectrum obtained from the analysis, along with the elements corresponding to the main peaks, is shown in Fig. 3
                     . Argon originates from the composition of the air, Silver from the walls of the X-ray tube, and Calcium most likely from the interlayer material printed between the part and its support, facilitating easy removal of the workpiece. In addition to Iron and Copper, several other contaminants can also be observed, like Manganese, Lead, Tin, Antimony and Rubidium.

Conducting the experiment at several average temperature levels between 15 and 54 K, we obtained the thermal conductivity values shown in Fig. 6
                     , which follow the expected trend for copper, where the thermal conductivity increases with decreasing temperature up to a peak and then starts to decrease again around 30-40 K. Comparing the results with previous low-temperature measurements found in the literature (shown on Fig. 7
                     ), we observe that our sample corresponds to copper with a purity level between RRR=10 and RRR=20 in terms of thermal conductivity. This makes it less attractive for cryogenic technical applications.
